The CSS Selector you're looking for is `[attribute=value]`. This will select elements that have an attribute with the value specified, regardless of what else it contains. For your example, it would look like this:
```css
[style="background-color: rgb(128, 128, 128);"] {
   /* styles here */
}
```<|endoftext|>

Here is one possible CSS selector that matches all elements that contain the specified background color value:

[attribute='value'] {
    /* styles */
}
In this example, the square brackets surrounding the attribute name indicate that we're selecting an attribute with a specific value. The double quotes around the value specify that it should be treated as a string literal. The braces {} around the value allow us to group selectors together and apply them simultaneously.

The second part of the selector sets the default style for all matching elements. In this case, we set the background color to red using RGB (red), and then we reset the background color to its original state by setting it to transparent. You can adjust the styling to fit your specific needs.<|endoftext|>

