module fsm_counting(input [7:0] data, // Data input from stream
                   output logic [3:0] count); // Output indicating count of 1s

  // States
  state counting {
    // Count up until we reach a certain number of 1s
    if (data[6]) begin
      count <= 7;
    end else if (data[5]) begin
      count <= 6;
    end else if (data[4]) begin
      count <= 5;
    end else begin
      count <= 4;
    end
  }

  // Idle state
  state idle {
    // Wait for another data input before starting again
    while (!data[7]) ;

    // Reset counter when we receive the end-of-stream signal
    count = 0;
  }

endmodule

In this example, the FSM has two states: counting and idle. In the counting state, the FSM counts the number of 1s in the data input stream using a series of conditional statements. If the sixth bit of the data input is a 1, the count increases by one. Similarly, if the fifth or fourth bits are also 1, the count increases by one respectively. If none of the six bits are 1, the count remains at four.

When the end-of-stream signal is received, the FSM transitions into the idle state where it resets its counter and waits for another data input. This ensures that the FSM only continues counting once all the 1s in the data input have been detected.

