\begin{document}

\begin{ Theorem }
Let $f:\R^n \to \C$ be an analytic function. Then there exists a unique polynomial $P(z) = \sum_{|\alpha| < n} c_\alpha z^\alpha$, where $c_\alpha \in \C$, such that $f(x) = P(\xi(x)))$ for all $x \in \R^n$. 
\end{ Theorem }

\begin{ Proof }
We will use the method of continuity to prove this result. Let's start by defining some functions. For each $\eta > 0$, let $u_{\eta}: \R^{2n+1} \to [0, 1]$ be a smooth cut-off function satisfying
$$ u_{\eta}(x, y) = 
    \begin{cases}
        1 & x_j - \eta < y_j < x_j + \eta \\
        0 & otherwise
    \end{cases}$$
for all $(x, y) \in \R^{2n+1}$. Similarly, define $v_{\eta}: \R^{2n+1} \to [0, 1]$ as follows:
$$ v_{\eta}(x, y) = 
    \begin{cases}
        1 & |y_i| < \eta \text{ or } x_i - \eta < y_i < x_i + \eta \text{ for any } i \\
        0 & otherwise
    \end{cases}$$
These are just smooth approximations to the indicator functions of the rectangles defined above. Now we can write our desired approximation formula in terms of these functions. We have
$$ f(x) = \lim_{\eta \to 0} \frac{1}{\eta} \int_{\R^{2n+1}} (u_{\eta} \circ T)(x, y) f(y) dy dx.$$
Since $T^{-1}$ is continuous on $\R^{2n+1}$, it follows from dominated convergence that
$$\lim_{\eta \to 0} \frac{1}{\eta} \int_{\R^{2n+1}} (u_{\eta} \circ T)(x, y) f(y) dy dx = \int_{\R^{2n+1}} uvdfdxdy.$$
Now we need to show that $uvdP = f$. To do this, first note that since both $u$ and $v$ vanish outside of the rectangle, we may integrate by parts twice to get
$$\begin{aligned}
   \int_{\R^{2n+1}} uvdP &= \int_{\R^{2n+1}} uvdFdxdy\\
&= F(x_1+\eta,...,x_{2n}+\eta,y_1-\eta,...,y_{2n}-\eta)-F(x_1,...,x_{2n},y_1,...,y_{2n})\\
&= f(x_1+\eta,...,x_{2n}+\eta,y_1-\eta,...,y_{2n}-\eta)-f(x_1,...,x_{2n},y_1,...,y_{2n}).
\end{aligned}$$
Therefore, we see that $uvdP=f$. This shows that the limit we obtained earlier indeed equals $f$, so we conclude that there exists a unique polynomial $P$ such that $f(x) = P(\xi(x)))$.<|endoftext|>

The Fundamental Theorem of Algebra states that every polynomial equation over the real numbers has either no solutions, one solution or infinitely many solutions.

Here is an example LaTeX document that demonstrates this theorem using aproof:
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{geometry}
